  <h2>Mulvane's Market: Small-Town Feel with Rural Options</h2>
  <p>Mulvane sits right on the Sedgwick-Sumner county line, about 20 miles south of Wichita. It's got that small-town feel — quieter, slower pace, more land. You get older downtown homes, newer suburban builds pushing north of town, and some properties with acreage outside city limits. It's not rural enough to be truly country, not close enough to be pure suburb. That in-between positioning attracts Boeing and Spirit workers who want more space than the metro offers but don't want a full commute.</p>
  <p>Mulvane sellers are often people looking for a lifestyle change, or people relocating for work who bought here for the value and now need to exit fast.</p>

  <h2>Mulvane Housing Stock and Market</h2>
  <p>Mulvane's price range is $120k-$220k typically. You've got older downtown homes from the early 1900s through 1950s mixed with newer suburban builds from the 1990s forward. Some properties sit on acreage outside city limits — that's different from Wichita proper. A lot of Mulvane homeowners are Boeing or Spirit workers who bought here because they could get more house for their money, or they wanted hobby farms and larger lots.</p>
  <p>The market's quieter than the suburbs closer to Wichita. Inventory moves slower. But when someone sells, they often have flexibility because they're not in a fast-growth urban market.</p>

  <h2>Who I Buy From in Mulvane</h2>
  <p>Boeing and Spirit workers relocating or changing jobs. People who bought Mulvane homes for the space and value, then got transferred closer to Wichita for work. Rural property owners looking to exit hobby farm situations. Estate sales from longtime residents. People inheriting property from parents. Folks who bought acreage, realized managing rural property is harder than they thought, and want to sell.</p>
  <p>Mulvane also sees people aging in place wanting to downsize but needing someone who understands both town and rural markets.</p>

